Override `CreateWindow` in your `App` class and attach handlers to all six events:

```csharp
public partial class App : Application
{
    protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
    {
        var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);

        window.Created     += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine("[Lifecycle] Created");
        window.Activated   += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine("[Lifecycle] Activated");
        window.Deactivated += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine("[Lifecycle] Deactivated");
        window.Stopped     += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine("[Lifecycle] Stopped");
        window.Resumed     += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine("[Lifecycle] Resumed");
        window.Destroying  += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine("[Lifecycle] Destroying");

        return window;
    }
}
```

**Key things to know:**

- On first launch the sequence is `Created → Activated` (no `Resumed`).
- `Deactivated` fires on focus loss (e.g. notification shade) — it doesn't mean the app backgrounded.
- `Resumed` only fires when returning from `Stopped`.
- On Android, the back button can skip `Stopped` and go straight to `Destroying`.

Output appears in your IDE's debug/application output window (Visual Studio Output pane or `dotnet` console with `System.Diagnostics.Debug`). Swap `Debug.WriteLine` for `ILogger` or `Console.WriteLine` if you need it in release builds.
